bug.short_desc: extension locations get's deleted when links-file is moved

long_desc.thetext:
Ciao @ll :) Consider this scenario: - install eclipse to /tmp/1 - install an extension location to /tmp/ext - register the ext-location with a link-file: /tmp/1/links/1.link - fire up eclipse
This will result in eclipse coming up with 2 sites, the platform:/base and the extension-location pointed to by 1.link.
If I - mv 1.link 2.link and fire up Eclipse again, the Extension location will be lost, due to code in PlatformConfiguration.validateSites(), this method removed ext locations whose link file is no longer there. However, one would expect the "new" link file to get a chance and re-register the extension location but that step fails due to a problematic sequence of events: 1.) The original sites are read 2.) The new link files are read and sites are registered IF the site does not exist yet 3.) invalid sites are removed via validateSites().
The second time eclipse is launched with the link-file in place the extension location is correctly registered again proving that things are just a lil out of order.
My suggestion here is to switch the succession above to this: 1.) The original sites are read 2.) invalid sites are removed via validateSites(). 3.) The new link files are read and sites are registered IF the site does not exist yet
I've done this locally by inserted one line at the beginning of PlatformConfiguration.findConfiguredSite(URL,boolean): "validateSites();"
Can you guys tell me what you think? My original problem is somewhat more complex but it boils down to this very "bug", or unfortunate behaviour... Thanks Guys :)
Any news on this one?
*ping* no reaction in over a year :(

bug.short_desc: Support annotated Java with suppressed interface pattern

long_desc.thetext: Created an attachment (id=50566) Source patch to consider superClass.
Created an attachment (id=50567) Compiled patch for 2.2.1

Ali,
Dave found some additional issue, one of which caused by the patch itself (when a class extends EObjectImpl after generating the code), so we will have to hold off committing this.

I'm changing this to a feature request, since I don't believe we could claim we've ever really supported annotated Java with the suppresed interface pattern. The fact that inheritance doesn't work, and has never worked, is a pretty good indication of that. ;)
The problem Ed refers to could be solved by generating an @extends tag on a root class for the root extends class and/or root extends interface.
Another problem I found: an unused import is generated if suppress interfaces is enabled and a root extends interface is specified. When you generate a derived class, GenClassImpl.getClassImplementsList() calls getInterfaceExtendsList(), which imports the root extends interface and returns a list containing the resulting base name. But then getClassImplementsList() takes that result and removes from it whatever it gets from calling getClassImplementsList() on the base GenClass (line 542). So the root extends interface won't appear in the implements list anymore, but it was already imported. It seems to me that getClassImplementsList() and getInterfaceExtendsList() shouldn't do any importing at all, if they're going to be used like this. The methods that call them should do all the importing.
Also, there should be support for non-default metadata packages.

This patch solves this problem always showing the user a system-based path and performing the URI encoding/desencoding internally. All labels that contained the word URI in the set of dialog boxes that deal with these references within the XML Catalogue were changes to "Location". long_desc.thetext:
When a component is registered in a bundle fragment, it is not activated. I've tested this against 3.3M1 SDK download at a Target Platform. I'll attach a ZIP file containing a bundle with a declarative service and a bundle fragment with a unique declarative service.
Please let me know if additional information is needed. Thanks.

Created an attachment (id=50590) Archive with two bundle projects
service-comp - bundle project with declarative service that writes to standard error on construction, activation and deactivation service-comp-fragment - bundle project that's hosted by service-comp; includes a different declarative service that writes to standard error on construction, activation and deactivation
When these bundles are run within Equinox (assuming auto startup), the service-comp's component will be activated, but service-comp-fragment's component is not.

I'm pretty sure the DS specification does not allow you to specify service components in fragments bundles. I will let BJ confirm.
If that is the case I would suggest you open a bug in the osgi bugzilla requesting a possible enhancement to the specification at http://bundles.osgi.org/bugzilla/

Maybe I'm reading this wrong bug in the OSGi R4 compendium document I found this comment (prior to logging the issue).
112.4 Component Description Component descriptions are defined in XML documents contained in a bundle and any attached fragments.
I just noticed this bit though:
112.4.1 ... A Service-Component manifest header specified in a fragment is ignored by SCR. However, XML documents referenced by a bundles Service-Component manifest header may be contained in attached fragments.
I'll try putting the header's reference to the file in the host bundle only.
Service-Component headers in fragments are ignored. But the Service-Component header in the host bundle can reference documents contained in fragments.
Thanks. Equinox does indeed find the files in a fragment. I'll resolve this as invalid.

bug.short_desc: Do not add project to EAR when adding J2EE facets to project

long_desc.thetext:
When "Add to EAR" is defaulted to on when creating a Web project, adding the Web facet to a faceted project triggers adding that project to an EAR (it might be the last EAR the user had used or the first EAR in the workspace). When we create a Web service in a service project in a service EAR with a non-existing client project, this caused the client project to be added to the service EAR. However, our code later on adds the client project to a client EAR. When both of these EARs are added to a server, this cause publish error since now we have 2 EARs containing WARs with the same context root.
This is not a problem in WTP 1.5.1 since "Add to EAR" is defaulted to be off. However, for products which has "Add to EAR" defaulted to on, this main user scenario (creating Web service with non-existing client project) is broken.
The fix to this problem is to set "Add to EAR" to false in the config object passed to the installProjectFacet operation when adding J2EE facets that could be put in an EAR. This includes the Web facet, EJB facet and App client facet.

Impact to user: In products build on top of WTP 1.5.1 which set ADD_TO_EAR to true by default, going through the Web Service wizard or Web Service Client wizard with a non-existing project will result in the wizard creating the project and adding that project to an EAR in the workspace. This is not the desirable behaviour since that newly created project is often not intended to be associated with an arbitrary EAR in the workspace. If the user choose to "assemble" the Web service, the Web service wizard actually create another EAR specified by the user and associate the project to it.
Impact of not fixing: When going through creation of Web service with non-existing client project (a very common scenario for Web service), the client project would be associated with the service EAR. This cause publish error when both the service EAR and a client EAR containing the same module is added to a server. The user would not be able to finish the Web service wizard successfully. The only workaround the user has would be to manually create the project and do the EAR association themselves if this problem is not fixed. Over the various releases, the user had counted on the Web service wizard doing this for them. This would be deem as a regression of behaviour.
The Fix:
The fix is very simple, isolated and safe. It only affects 1 file.
We create projects by created a facet project and then adding the required facets to it. When we add facets to project using the ProjectFacet.modify method, instead of just passing a null config object to the Action (which is the input parameter to the modify method), we check to see if the facet being added is a J2EE facet that could be added to an EAR (jst.web, jst.ejb, jst.utility, jst.appclient). If it is, we create the corresponding data model, set ADD_TO_EAR to false and pass this data model in as the config object.
This patch has been well tested and we are seeking approval to drop this into WTP 1.5.1.
Created an attachment (id=50637) Patch for jst.ws.consumption plugin

This problem is a serious regression. By far the most common golden path thru the Web service wizards is to have them automatically generate, assemble, deploy and start a Web service and client to any combination of new or existing projects. They were designed for this. Where the client project does not exist - again, an extremely common case when creating or consuming Web services - the Web service wizard cannot be completed.
The good news is Kathy's patch very elegantly solves the issue precisely where we add facets to projects. The facet Actions are simply adjusted to include a DataModel with ADD_TO_EAR disabled. Virtually all the new code here (in the new getConfigObject private method) simply detects "EAR friendly" facets and sets the ADD_TO_EAR property to false. The J2EE folks have also helped review the change.
PMC, would you please approve this as soon as possible? It will not be acceptable to users and adopters to release WTP 1.5.1's Web service wizards without this fix.
Kathy, excellent patch. Thanks for working on this.

+1 This does look like an elegant fix! My only observation is that getConfigObject looks like it should return a type of IDataModel, instead of Object, but that's just from a quick read and up to you.

bug.short_desc: [Web connector] Streamline web connector UI

long_desc.thetext:
Rob, Gail and I had a discussion about the UI for the web connector and how to streamline it in order to ensure that it is simple enough to be part of 1.0, i.e. to hide the implementation details enough to have it usable by non-experts. Here is the interaction that we came up with:
1) Create a new web connector repository from a template as happens now. By default the page will have "anonymous" login checked and probably not editable (but for bug 151602 repository-specific credentials will be supported).
2) Create a query. The query page should be populated by the settings specified for the repository. For a typical interaction the user should not need to modify any string on this page other than the URL (i.e. the regexp and prefix get generated from parameters on the repository settings page).
I think that the above also provide compelling reasons to keep the repositories and queries separate. Thoughts?
I just notice that we have bug 155160 already, which covers (2) above. But we can continue to use this one for general discussion.

Mik, I am not completely sure if suggested UI will fit for all cases. For instance, it does not fit well when repostory can have more then one query. SourceForge (you have to have separate queries for bugs and enhancement requests), Google hosting and some others do allow many queries per repository.
Also note that now we don't have custom UI for web connector. It is using generic repository prefs.

We definitely need to support multiple queries per repository. But wouldn't that work well as suggested here? The user just has to specify a different URL for each query, which I'm hoping for most cases they will get to paste from the browser. But the key thing is that they won't have to care about the regexp, etc, since that will be generated from the repository settings.
I wasn't thinking that this required custom UI (anonymous is already generic, seems like other things can be attributes). But if needed we can make the UI there customizable by the connector.

It is somehow twisted. The only field that can be copied from repository settings is the task url prefix. That field is somehow redundant, because in general prefix can be specific to query (not repository). E.g. SourceForge and GForge have that issue. And the only reason we have prefix on repository is to be able to add existing tasks. I think if we'll change "add existing task" wizard to request both id and the full task url (somehow similar to current weblinked tasks) we can remove prefix from the repository settings.
We can also check if one of query templates does match with selected repository url and then fill in query form from that template, but that obviously won't work if user configured his own repository. So, I don't see lot of value in providing this feature.

We still need to figure out how to simplify this UI to make it part of 1.0, because currently it is only suitable for very advanced users (i.e. surfaces way too much implementation detail). Or alternatively we can explore making sandbox components available with release builds (e.g. via a separate update site). Both are fine solutions from my point of view, but I'd still like to explore whether it can be simple enough to become part of the regular distribution.
Here's how I see it: all web repositories that we know of use the following conventions for accessing projects (correct me if I'm wrong): * http://a.b/c.cgi${project.id} * ${project.url}/a/b.php * http://a.b/${project.dir}/c
For the common case, the only information that the user should need to provide is the ${project.mumble} identifier. So that should be stored on the repository. All the formats then use the identifier and information from the template (e.g. regexp used for query, task prefix URL used for matching, new task URL used for wizard). So on the query page, the user does not need to modify anything, unless they want to paste in a modified URL (e.g. to not list all tasks but a subset). We may also need to hide (e.g. collapse) the regexp by default because any UI that exposes regexp is by definition advanced, and hopefully the user will only need edit the regexp if they have customized HTML presentation (and in that case their repository admin should provide a template).
Let me know what you think, or if you have other UI simplification ideas to make this usable by non-experts. But it's also totally fine for us to decide that this is an inherently expert mode of working (relying on parsing web page output), and that the implementation details can not be hidden in a sufficiently generic way, and make this a Sandbox tool. Thinking out of the box only other alternative I see is creating non-generic but tracker-specific web connectors that can come with more advanced pre-configuration than the templates can provide (i.e. each would be it's own connector).
I'm CC'ing Raphael since he is the only one I know to have used the web connector, in case he has any feedback.

(Please let me know if this comment gets too off-topic and should be in a different bug) I was actually going to propose to make the web connector UI even more advanced, by adding support for mapping other properties of tasks than id and name, such as whether it is completed, priority etc. But this would actually need some kind of mapping functions which either would require complex UI and would be hard to develop or could be done in Java and provided with the templates. What if in a template extension you could add a class that implements a specific interface and can map query results to task properties. (Maybe I'm way off here, I'm not very familiar with all the internals)
But I definitely think all the advanced UI should be hidden by default, maybe letting the user specify only a project ID (as was detailed in bug 155160)
---
An idea I just had is to add another more complex generic connector that can use BIRT as it's input and develop the queries as BIRT reports with custom data sources. But I'm not even sure how possible / hard to do that is or if it would be easy enough to use.
What could be done about generic repository support for repositories that expose some web services? For example new versions of ChangeLogic add some SOAP web services, including one for querying tasks.
Maybe this would be too complex to do in the scope of Mylar and should be left to some external add-on?

Erkki: I see your suggestion along the following lines: if we could understand the format that was returned by some web server by transforming it by some well-defined rule, then we could map these fields. We could take this a step further: we could define the XML format for a bug and a query, and then off-load the task of transforming it onto the repository provider. For example, we could ask that if a query is specified with &ctype=mylar-xml then we get back XML that we understand. Understanding tasks in this format would then be the main job of the generic web connector, and repository providers could implement various capabilities.

bug.short_desc: [CheatSheet] Request to enhance OpenCheatSheetAction to accept a String containing raw XML as input

long_desc.thetext:
Currently, the simple cheat sheet editor uses the OpenCheatSheetAction to launch a cheat sheet. This is done by specifying the URL to the cheat sheet XML file as one of the constructors parameters.
In order to implement a clean and performance-sensitive solution for Bug #157603, it would be convenient if the OpenCheatSheetAction had a separate constructor that accepted a String containing the raw XML of the cheat sheet file. That way, the cheat sheet editor could serialize the unsaved editor input into a String and hand it directly to the open cheat sheet action without going through and intermediate file.

This seems reasonable enough. I don't see any major drawback to adding an extra constructor in the API. Dejan - what do you think? If we were to do this I think that there is no need to save the state of the cheat sheet when it is closed. Here's what the new constructor might look like: /** * Creates an action that opens a cheat sheet using * XML passed in as a string * * @param id the id to give this cheat sheet * @param name the name to give this cheat sheet * @param xml the cheatsheet content in xml format * @exception IllegalArgumentException if the parameters * are null * @since 3.3 */ public OpenCheatSheetAction(String id, String name, String xml) I've included the name and id parameters to match public OpenCheatSheetAction(String id, String name, URL url) { but I could be persuaded to leave the name out since it does not seem to serve much useful purpose.

Created an attachment (id=50615) Patch with provisional fix
Here's a patch with you can test out which adds a new constructor to OpenCheatSheetAction. If it looks OK and we all agree on adding the new API I can clean up the code and commit next week.

Chris, this seems fine. Mike, please try the patch and let us know if it works for you.
Mike, Chris, make sure you agree on the ecoding. In order to open the byte stream on a cheat sheet, we need to know the encoding (e.g. UTF-8).

I've implemented a fix for Bug #157603 using Chris' patch and works very well and fits cleanly with existing editor code. If the editor is dirty, I preview using the String. If the editor is not dirty, I preview using the URL.
I need to discuss the encoding issue with Wassim; but, I'm pretty sure it will end up being UTF-8 as the default.

I've tested out the preview function with input that gave the plug-in manifest source editor problems: encontrar algum erro nessas pgina
In the manifest editor case, parsing failed due to the following error message: java.io.UTFDataFormatException: Invalid byte 2 of 3-byte UTF-8 sequence.
However, the cheat sheet parser (which uses a DOM parser) parses the input fine without having to specify an encoding. The input is represented properly in the cheat sheet view.
The reason for this is because a org.xml.sax.InputSource wrapping a StringReader is used as input to the parser.
From Javadoc:
"The SAX parser will use the InputSource object to determine how to read XML input. If there is a character stream available, the parser will read that stream directly, disregarding any text encoding declaration found in that stream."
Since, we are not parsing from file and the native Java encoding is UTF-16, we avoid the problems of the plug-in manifest editor and avoid having to convert the input to a byte array to do an explicit encoding conversion.

The change that I made for 105824 was a fix to a regression introduced by Scott's initial 105824 changes. If you rolled back from 1.7 to 1.6 and the problem went away, then my regression fix caused your problem. If you went back from 1.7 to 1.5, then Scott's initial fix to 105824 caused your problem.
Scott's fix for 105824 addressed a problem where, when dealing with workbench machines with aggressive firewalls that refused connections back from the AC on server sockets that they created, our inability to create a console resulted in our inability to do anything with those systems. His fix added a new command that checks to see if the agent controller machine can "reach" some other machine (in this case, the workbench) on a specific port. If the new command determines that the server is reachable, then the behavior of my fix is a no-op. If the new command determines that the server is unreachable, then the behavior of my fix is to prevent a hang and allow the execution to continue (which was the intent of Scott's fix.) I don't see how that could be the cause of your problem.
If you rolled back to version 1.5 of the file and found that the problem went away, then it's clear that the new ServerReachCommand is incorrectly concluding that the workbench is unreachablable from the agent machine on the port in question. bug.short_desc: Threads with detail UNSPECIFIED should not expand

long_desc.thetext:
Version: 3.2.1 Build id: M20060915-1045
This is a timing issue. I don't have an easy testcase but let me explain what I have discovered.
My debug engine requires that when a step is initiated (doesn't matter which thread) all threads are resumed. The thread selected when the step is requested sends a resume with STEP detail. All the rest of the threads are resumed with UNSPECIFIED detail. When the debuggee has finished stepping I send a series of suspends. The first suspend with STEP_DONE is sent for the thread that is considered the stopping thread. I then send a suspend UNSPECIFIED for all the other threads.
Running normally the wrong thread is selected. If I stop before I send the first suspend the last thread that had a resume UNSPECIFIED is selected. (I don't understand why sending a resume with UNSPECIFIED would cause a thread to be selected) When the last suspend with UNSPECIFIED is sent I consistently get the wrong thread selected.
But if I slow down the sending of the suspend events (by adding a sleep) the correct thread is selected. It is as if giving enough time between sending the suspends allows the first suspend with STEP_DONE to get the selection correct.
The expected behaviour is that the thread with the first SUSPEND + STEP_DONE will expand and get selected. The other threads will suspend but won't affect the selection since the first suspended thread should always stay selected.

We have a problem with the CDT debugger that looks very much like this one. Our debug engine (gdb) also requires to resume all threads when stepping. When the target is suspended the attempt to switch to another thread and step results in the selection of the previously selected thread. I suspect that the view restores the old selection after the right thread is selected. I have spent some time unsuccesfully chasing the bug, but unfortunately I currently don't have an environment to reproduce it.
Marking as 3.2.2 candidate. Needs investigation.
*** Bug 158185 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***

It seems that this patch in combination with a (not yet approved) one-line fix in CDT 3.1.1 solves the problem with 155464. I have tested it for a few hours and I haven't found any problems. The one-line fix in CDT 3.1.1 fires resume events with UNSPECIFIED detail (instead of CLIENT_REQUEST detail as originally) for all resumed threads except the current thread.
I really hope this patch makes it into Eclipse 3.2.2. Debugging of multi-threaded programs with CDT and GDB certainly depends on it.
Alan (original problem reporter) was unable to verify that this patch fixed his problem, so it has not been applied to 3.2.2 yet.

Alan, have you verified this patch so that it can be approved? If not, do you still agree with the patch and approve of it?
Multithreaded debugging with Eclipse/CDT/GDB really needs this patch and it would be great if it made it into Eclipse 3.2.2. Otherwise, multithreaded debugging with Eclipse/CDT/GDB will not work correctly and that would be a shame for such an otherwise great C/C++ development environment.

We discovered that the problem Alan was having does *not* require a fix in the debug platform. In Alan's case a thread step started in one thread, but execution suspended in another thread (breakpoint) where the entire debug target was suspended. Alan wanted the "breakpoint" thread to have focus, but the default model proxy/selection policy does not support this (since the step has not completed and a frame already has focus). Alan got around this problem by overriding the default model selection policy.
I would prefer not to inject this fix into 3.2.2 if there are alternate solutions. In the Java debugger, when a VM suspends due to a breakpoint we fire 2 events - a suspend event for the target and a suspend event for the thread where the breakpoint was hit. We don't fire suspend events for the other threads and they do not expand (even they are suspended). It could be that there is similar solution for this problem in the CDT debugger?

There is so called "current thread" in gdb, so we fire one suspend event for the current thread and change state events for others to repaint the labels. But all threads are in the suspended state.

The debug view does not preserve selection on RESUME/CLIENT_REQUEST. In this case, the thread is refreshed and usually collapses (since it will be running and have no stack frames). On a RESUME/STEP_OVER the thread remains expanded with the stack frame selected, assuming a SUSPEND/STEP_END will arrive soon. When the suspend (step end) is encountered we update to select the top frame in the thread (which is usually the same one that was already selected, unless a step out or into was performed).
In Alan's case, a breakpoint was hit in another thread after the STEP_OVER and before the the STEP_END. However, the model selection policy was precluding the breakpoint thread from being selected, since a frame already had focus and was waiting for the STEP_END.

To reproduce our case we do the following steps: 1. The session is suspended and the first thread is current and expanded. 2. Expand the second thread, select it's top frame and step over it. 3. The stack frames of the first thread are removed. 4. When the session is suspended both threads are expanded and the top frame of the first thread is selected. Internally the suspend event is fired only for the second thread, but for some reason the first thread is expanded and it's top frame is selected.
